declare function getOutcome(): SuccessOrFailure;

const outcome = getOutcome();

type Outcome = typeof outcome extends "success"? "success" : "failure";

function handleOutcome(result: Outcome) {
  if (result === "success") {
    //...
  } else {
    //...
  }
}

handleOutcome(outcome);
```
In this example, we first declare a union type `SuccessOrFailure` with possible values of "success" or "failure". We then use the `getOutcome` function to get a value of type `SuccessOrFailure`.

Next, we use the conditional type `Outcome` to infer the actual type of the `outcome` variable, based on the value it holds. We use the "satisfies" operator (`extends`) and the "infer" keyword to achieve this. The type `Outcome` will be "success" if the value of `outcome` is "success" and "failure" otherwise.

